These are the files for the Reddit Upvote/Downvote Button Enclosure I built to fit a project I was working on. This is just barely big enough to fit a Teensy development board and a couple of buttons. I've included the code and better instructions on the project itself on my blog here: http://www.thenewhobbyist.com/2011/07/am-i-doing-this-right-reddit-upvote-button/ I've also included in the images for this thing my wiring diagram if you'd like to take a shot at making your own. Being able to print a project box to my exact dimensions was as expected, awesome. Here's a video of it in action:
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yNkKHRwk3MA&feature=player_embedded New Museum Challenge Notes: The ability to 3D model and print the enclosure and buttons for this project allowed me to make design decisions that would not have been possible using conventional methods. The arrow buttons for example, are not available through any distributor I could find commercially. Additionally the enclosure itself is the exact size (down to the millimeter) to fit my electronics. I believe the conventional idea of using off the shelf parts and fitting your designs into them is coming to an end. The ability to translate my vision for this project to a physical object would not be possible without access to a 3D printer.

• Print top, bottom and arrows. Arrows can be printed in white and colored or printed in complimentary colors.

description.text:
My Build plate arm reinforcement is done.
The arm is a lot stiffer now. The system has 8 parts that need to be printed out for one side and 3 carbon fiber 8mm square rod parts.
Also you need 35 screws per side. Those 8 parts is assemble to 4 parts that will hold the carbon fiber rod in place.
The carbon fiber rod is 3 parts that will fit into those plastic part that you printed. Those 4 parts is fasten into the arm with plastic plugs that you expand with a screw.
This make the whole system to be bolted on the arm without any damage on the arm. It will make the arm a lot more stiff and I hope it will also prevent the arm to warp due the heat and time. To make this system you need this for each side .
Print out the plastic parts.
29 screws to the covers.
6 screws ( shorter) to the ex-pander plugs in the parts.
350mm long 8mm carbon fiber square rod. I did spend totally $15-20 for both sides. After you have printed your parts, let them cool down.
Then measure them so the channels in them is max 8mm.
If its bigger then the carbon fiber rod will be to small and the whole system will not work.
How good the parts will be depending on your printer, slicer and your settings.
If the channels is to small you can always use a file to make them a bit bigger, but do NOT make them bigger then 8mm wide. Also if you print out the arm plug part first you can measure that and do what needed to make the part to be as good it can, before you print the rest. You will also know what screw size you need. The hole is 3mm in the bottom part and 3.5mm on the upper part. It did get better then I did think it would be. It will not flex much at all.
To be true the back round rod that the arm is on do flex when I push in the front of the arm.

I made the plastic parts in 123D Design.
I did print out those parts with makerware latest version.
Most parts need support. The carbon fiber square rod I did buy from a shop that sells carbon fiber stuff.

description.text:
Some people have built very complicated solutions for mounting plexiglas walls on a Solidoodle 3 to keep the heat in.  All I did was stick magnets to some sheets of plexiglas, which worked fine, until the magnets started to fail.  So here's my idea for a super-simple solution.  
This clip is very small, uses very little filament, and prints fast.  (Though I've had mixed results trying to print six at a time -- I only get a few that work and a few that come out mangled -- but you might do better than me.)  
The downside?  It doesn't hold in the plexiglas as airtight as some of you may want.  But it holds it in more than well enough for successful printing.  
I've included a Google SketchUp file for those who want to remix it.

Print up six (or nine, for more strength) of them.  You'll find they will slip over the frame of the Solidoodle 3 (might fit the 2 as well, but I don't know).  Position two on each side, one near (but not quite at) each end.  If you printed nine, put the extras in the middle.  Then crazy-glue the plexiglass to them.  See the picture I posted of one side of my SD3 held in this way.  
Thus, the plexiglas is held on the SD3 frame, but can be fairly easily removed.  (This clip has just a bit of "slack" to make it easy for them to be removed, in fact.)  Of course, this depends on the fact that your plexiglas is light (this could never work for actual glass) and that your glue is strong.  
You may still benefit from magnets stuck to the bottom inside of the plexiglas.  Helps it stick to the frame, without also having to bear the weight of the plexiglas.

I always liked how Ken Block had that vertical lever for his E-Brake in his Gymkhana videos so that's how I decided on a vertical knob.  I have one in my Mustang, with the nut epoxied into the recession, not being held by screws like this current model is, but it's holding up fine.  Only had it in there a week though. Notes: For the main piece, it really should be printed with it's long axis parallel to the print bed, that when when you shift the force is perpendicular to the layers. If the force is parallel to the layers, there's a very good chance it'll break. The pistol grip has two files, I made mine in NinjaFlex so without the rib I added it was rocking back and forth as the toolhead moved over it and had a pretty bad surface finish. I included one without the rib in case you want to do it in hard plastic. I printed it without supports and it came out fine.

If you print the pistol grip with the rib, you're gonna wanna use a really sharp exacto knife to slice it off. Kinda hard to get in there but it's certainly do able. Slide a M12-1.25 nut into the large hole at the bottom of the main piece and screw the small bottom piece on with two nuts that can be found here (http://www.mcmaster.com/#96068a159/=z5k6ad). You don't have to use those, if you do it with ABS I included one without the holes and you could probably acetone weld them together. Then, with your empty shift lever, thread a second M12-1.25 (preferably with a nylon lock) to the bottom of the threads, then screw the knob all the way down and line it up so it's comfortable to shift with, and tighten the lower nut up against the knob to lock it in place. Feel free to message me with other questions.

I will add more photos as I finish the complete skull replication. Enjoy and thank the awesome scientists who make this kind of reproduction possible. All specimens and original scans are attributable to the original authors. I am an anthropologist NOT affiliated with this project or the Rising Star team. I teach anthropology and specialize in fetal osteology and 3D reconstruction, and I have several specimens available at https://www.etsy.com/shop/FetalReproductions?ref=hdr_shop_menu, including a high-resolution fetal scans, bones, and other interesting specimens, and be sure to check out my page at https://www.facebook.com/FetalReproductions/ and drop me a line.

description.text: I put a center hole in 3 of my panels just in case.

On discussion with Vik and how he wanted to setup a place that sells RepRap kits in, and seeing as I needed extruder bits for my RepStrap, I set forth to use the bits from the RepRap Subversion.
There is a big problem with the drawings of the extruder bits, from ease of changing nozzles to a general lack of missing dimensions and also attempting to remove some known problems with them. So here are all the refined versions of them, with two types of nozzles.
The two types are,
Fully machined and have the NT extension (NT means no text, as the first version had text on it, but it became way too expensive to produce, hence the NT version)
Domed nut version. The domed nut version is very cost effective, and can be purchased virtually anywhere, i've only included the NT version for people to play with if they want, as most people will wan the domed nut version. You may notice a 0.2mm dimension there, and this was once a proposed future extrusion size. The drill its that need to be bought for it have a short drillable depth of less than 2mm, thus a domed nut version is the way to go for this size of extrusion. The domed nut nozzle is also cheaper to produce than the MakerBot nozzle. The parts are designed to make use of local CNC or machining companies or businesses, hence the need for more dimensions. Enjoy!

The parts go together as you\'d normally expect, however, the heater barrel needs to be as tight as possible in the thermal barrier For this you'll need a 12mm spanner.
2 x M6 nuts, do not use the nozzles at this stage.
A 10mm spanner for the M6 nuts
M6 flat washer
Zip tie Screw the heater barrel into the thermal barrier by hand,
Screw on an M6 nut and screw it down near the bottom, leaving about a 2mm gap from the thermal barrier,
Screw the second M6 nut down to the first,
Using both spanners tighten the barrel into the thermal barrier, by using the second M6 nut and the thermal barrier. Once those two bits are tightened, loosen the nuts on the thermal barrier by screwing DOWN further the first M6 nut closest to the thermal barrier, if you left enough gap this will be easy, then UNSCREW the second nut off the barrel, then the first nut. Put on an M6 flat washer onto the barrel.
Screw on a nozzle, tighten if you can to about 1Nm of torque <- IMPORTANT don't over tighten nozzle. Then the rest of the assembly is as per normal, with nichrome wire and thermistor/thermocouple, using your choice of Kapton tape and/or fire cement Finally use a zip tie to keep all those wires from flying about, use the flats used in assembly of the thermal barrier to secure them down.

description.text:
These are very basic fan ducts with an open design to allow for easy access to the hot end for maintenance. Most useful for those who have transitioned to the Olsson block or regularly change nozzles.
I wanted ducts that were compact, allow for easy access to the hot end, and allow for some cooling when required. I don't regularly run my fans so extreme cooling is not a priority for me, although I'm sure these ducts should be more than adequate for most hobbyists. 
I've included single files and a print all in one STL. The only hardware you should have to source are 4 M3x8mm screws. The hanging points have been thickened for added support and avoid cracking as most printed fan ducts do. For the mounting of my fans I only used 2 screws and that's more than enough to keep them firmly in place.
These ducts will remain marked a work in progress for about a month in case any changes are made.

comments.text: I haven't suffered any issues yet, but I don't consistently run fans like most do unless it involves alot of overhangs. description.text: This is a remix with a new blower design so high temp materials can be printed for extended time without overheating the aluminum block on the Mk8 extruder.. It just redirects the air upward above the heating block to cool the stem of the extruder. works up to 260C on long prints with block barely warm. This blower nozzle prints much better than stock Mk8 because it actively cools the print to stop slow movements on small parts from melting the part or worse yet warping the outer edges up as is so common. You will need a fan such as this one , mine had no plug so just clip off old and resolder.. http://www.ebay.com/itm/12V-DC-50mm-Blow-Radial-Cooling-Fan-Hotend-Extruder-For-RepRap-3D-Printer-/321759211222?hash=item4aea57eed6 It also includes the missing endstop arm to hit the X axis sensor. Straight version is for the modified Zaxis carriage and other is for the stock i3 X - Zcarriage. Annd print the blower nozzle on the smallest side down rotate 90deg+- ..

My wife needed to count quite a bit of change for a school fundraiser where all the children brought in as many pennies as they could on Monday, followed by nickels on Tuesday, Dimes on Wednesday et cetera, et cetera. Ultimately I know she was going to have to count several hundred dollars in change. I did a quick search on Thingiveerse and did not really find anything that would meet my needs. The closest item was the Coin Sorter and Counting/Wrapping Tubes by HPaul, https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:11322, but they were designed for a very small print bed and required several glue ups. I also noticed in the comments that there were alignment issues. So I decided to quickly design my own. This project prints four sorting trays and four counting tubes for US quarters, nickels, pennies and dimes. The counting tubes have a funnel to quickly channel the coins into the counter, and an overflow slot when you reached your proper count. The trays have chamfers on top and bottom so they easily stack and lock when shaking/sorting. When making the slots on the coin counting tubes, I opted not to use supports. I ended up folding up some card stock and literally holding it against the tube at the right time, and allowing the printer to print on the paper 6-8 laps before I tugged he paper away. It worked surprisingly well.I'll try to record a video of the technique. This was designed and printed using ABS. I chose to color code the rays and counters for simplicity. I used a 40% fill as is a habit for me on my designs.
